SIMPLE: patent
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Patent
<hw>Pat"ent</hw> <pr>(p⟦acr⟧t"<it>e</it>nt ⟦or⟧
p⟦amac⟧t"<it>e</it>nt)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>patens</ets>,
<ets>-entis</ets>, p. pr. of <ets>patere</ets> to be open: cf. F.
<ets>patent</ets>. Cf. <er>Fathom</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<note>(<xex>Oftener pronounced</xex> <pr>p⟦amac⟧t"<it>e</it>nt</pr>
<xex>in this sense</xex>)</note> <def>Open; expanded; evident; apparent;
unconcealed; manifest; public; conspicuous.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He had received instructions, both <qex>patent</qex> and
secret.</q> <rj><qau>Motley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Open to public perusal; -- said of a document
conferring some right or privilege; <as>as, letters
<ex>patent</ex></as>. See <cref>Letters patent</cref>, under 3d
<er>Letter</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Appropriated or protected by letters patent; secured
by official authority to the exclusive possession, control, and disposal
of some person or party; patented; <as>as, a <ex>patent</ex> right;
<ex>patent</ex> medicines.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Madder . . . in King Charles the First's time, was made a
<qex>patent</qex> commodity.</q> <rj><qau>Mortimer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Spreading; forming a nearly right
angle with the steam or branch; <as>as, a <ex>patent</ex>
leaf</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Patent leather</b></col>, <cd>a varnished or lacquered
leather, used for boots and shoes, and in carriage and harness
work.</cd> -- <col><b>Patent office</b></col>, <cd>a government bureau
for the examination of inventions and the granting of patents.</cd> --
<col><b>Patent right</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>The exclusive right to
an invention, and the control of its manufacture</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd>
<fld>(Law)</fld> <cd>The right, granted by the sovereign, of exclusive
control of some business of manufacture, or of the sale of certain
articles, or of certain offices or prerogatives.</cd> -- <col><b>Patent
rolls</b></col>, <cd>the registers, or records, of
patents.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Patent</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Patent
<hw>Pat"ent</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>patente</ets>. See
<er>Patent</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A letter patent,
or letters patent; an official document, issued by a sovereign power,
conferring a right or privilege on some person or party.</def>
Specifically: <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A writing securing to an
invention.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A document making a grant and
conveyance of public lands.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Four other gentlemen of quality remained mentioned in that
<qex>patent</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In the United States, by the act of 1870, patents for
inventions are issued for seventeen years, without the privilege of
renewal except by act of Congress.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The right or privilege conferred by such a document;
hence, figuratively, a right, privilege, or license of the nature of a
patent.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If you are so fond over her iniquity, give her <qex>patent</qex>
to offend.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Patent</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Patent
<hw>Pat"ent</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Patented</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Patenting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To grant by patent; to make the
subject of a patent; to secure or protect by patent; <as>as, to
<ex>patent</ex> an invention; to <ex>patent</ex> public
lands.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Patentable</ent>⟦br⟧
